# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: code-generation-templates
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:code-generation-templates/automatic-programming] In computer science, **automatic programming** is a type of computer programming in which some mechanism generates a computer program, to allow human programmers to write the code at a higher abstraction level.
[src:code-generation-templates/automatic-programming] There has been little agreement on the precise definition of automatic programming, mostly because its meaning has changed over time.
[src:code-generation-templates/automatic-programming] David Parnas, tracing the history of "automatic programming" in published research, noted that in the 1940s it described automation of the manual process of punching paper tape.
[src:code-generation-templates/automatic-programming] Later it referred to translation of high-level programming languages like Fortran and ALGOL.
[src:code-generation-templates/automatic-programming] One of the earliest programs identifiable as a compiler is named Autocode.
[src:code-generation-templates/automatic-programming] Program synthesis is one type of automatic programming where a procedure is created from scratch, based on mathematical requirements.
[src:code-generation-templates/automatic-programming] Mildred Koss, an early UNIVAC programmer, explains: "Writing machine code involved several tedious steps—breaking down a process into discrete instructions, assigning specific memory locations to all the commands, and managing the I/O buffers.
[src:code-generation-templates/automatic-programming] After following these steps to implement mathematical routines, a sub-routine library, and sorting programs, our task was to look at the larger programming process.
[src:code-generation-templates/automatic-programming] We needed to understand how we might reuse tested code and have the machine help in programming.
[src:code-generation-templates/automatic-programming] As we programmed, we examined the process and tried to think of ways to abstract these steps to incorporate them into higher-level language.
[src:code-generation-templates/automatic-programming] The goal is to improve programmer productivity.
[src:code-generation-templates/automatic-programming] It is often related to code-reuse topics such as component-based software engineering.
[src:code-generation-templates/automatic-programming] Modern programming languages are well supported by tools like Json4Swift (Swift) and Json2Kotlin (Kotlin).
[src:code-generation-templates/automatic-programming] These application generators supported COBOL inserts and overrides.
[src:code-generation-templates/automatic-programming] A macro processor, such as the C preprocessor, which replaces patterns in source code according to relatively simple rules, is a simple form of source-code generator.
[src:code-generation-templates/automatic-programming] Source-to-source code generation tools also exist.
[src:code-generation-templates/automatic-programming] Large language models such as ChatGPT are capable of generating a program's source code from a description of the program given in a natural language.
[src:code-generation-templates/automatic-programming] Many relational database management systems (RDBMS) provide a function that will export the content of the database as SQL data definition queries, which may then be executed to re-import the tables and their data, or migrate them to another RDBMS.
[src:code-generation-templates/automatic-programming] Some languages use *annotations* to generate source code and inject it.
[src:code-generation-templates/automatic-programming] For example, this is done in Java and Kotlin using annotations, for example the Project Lombok library which runs at compile time with an annotation processor.
[src:code-generation-templates/automatic-programming] There has been a C++ proposal to add token sequence injection using compile-time reflective programming (reflection).
[src:code-generation-templates/automatic-programming] A low-code development platform (LCDP) is software that provides an environment programmers use to create application software through graphical user interfaces and configuration instead of traditional computer programming.
[src:code-generation-templates/automatic-programming] Vibe coding is a software development practice assisted by artificial intelligence (AI) where the software developer describes a project or task in a prompt to a large language model (LLM) which generates source code automatically.
[src:code-generation-templates/automatic-programming] Vibe coding may involve accepting AI-generated code without thorough review of the output, instead relying on results and follow-up prompts to guide changes.
[src:code-generation-templates/automatic-programming] The term was coined in February 2025 by computer scientist Andrej Karpathy, a co-founder of OpenAI and former AI leader at Tesla.
[src:code-generation-templates/automatic-programming] Merriam-Webster listed the term in March 2025 as a "slang & trending" expression.
[src:code-generation-templates/automatic-programming] It was named the *Collins English Dictionary* Word of the Year for 2025.
[src:code-generation-templates/automatic-programming] Advocates of vibe coding say that it allows even amateur programmers to produce software without the extensive training and skills required for software engineering.
[src:code-generation-templates/automatic-programming] Critics point out a lack of accountability, maintainability, and an increased risk of introducing security vulnerabilities in the resulting software.
[src:code-generation-templates/code-generation-compiler] In computing, **code generation** is part of the process chain of a compiler, in which an intermediate representation of source code is converted into a form (e.g., machine code) that the target system can readily execute.
[src:code-generation-templates/code-generation-compiler] Sophisticated compilers typically perform multiple passes over various intermediate forms.
[src:code-generation-templates/code-generation-compiler] This multi-stage process is used because many algorithms for code optimization are easier to apply one at a time, or because the input to one optimization relies on the completed processing performed by another optimization.
[src:code-generation-templates/code-generation-compiler] This organization also facilitates the creation of a single compiler that can target multiple architectures, as only the last of the code generation stages (the *backend*) needs to change from target to target.
[src:code-generation-templates/code-generation-compiler] The input to the code generator typically consists of a parse tree or an abstract syntax tree.
[src:code-generation-templates/code-generation-compiler] The tree is converted into a linear sequence of instructions, usually in an intermediate language such as three-address code.
[src:code-generation-templates/code-generation-compiler] Further stages of compilation may or may not be referred to as "code generation", depending on whether they involve a significant change in the representation of the program.
[src:code-generation-templates/code-generation-compiler] In addition to converting an intermediate representation into a linear sequence of machine instructions, a typical code generator tries to optimize the generated code.
[src:code-generation-templates/code-generation-compiler] In a compiler that uses an intermediate language, there may be two instruction selection stages—one to convert the parse tree into intermediate code, and a second phase, much later, to convert the intermediate code into instructions from the instruction set of the target machine.
[src:code-generation-templates/code-generation-compiler] This second phase does not require a tree traversal; it can be done linearly, and typically involves a simple replacement of intermediate-language operations with their corresponding opcodes.
[src:code-generation-templates/code-generation-compiler] However, suppose the compiler is a language translator (for example, one that converts Java to C++).
[src:code-generation-templates/code-generation-compiler] In that case, the second code-generation phase may involve *building* a tree from the linear intermediate code.
[src:code-generation-templates/code-generation-compiler] When code generation occurs at runtime, as in just-in-time compilation (JIT), the entire process must be efficient with respect to space and time.
[src:code-generation-templates/code-generation-compiler] For example, when regular expressions are interpreted and used to generate code at runtime, a non-deterministic finite-state machine is often generated instead of a deterministic one because the former can usually be created more quickly and occupies less memory space than the latter.
[src:code-generation-templates/code-generation-compiler] Despite generally generating less efficient code, JIT code generation can take advantage of profiling information that is available only at runtime.
[src:code-generation-templates/code-generation-compiler] The fundamental task of taking input in one language and producing output in a non-trivially different language can be understood in terms of the core transformational operations of formal language theory.
[src:code-generation-templates/code-generation-compiler] Consequently, some techniques initially developed for use in compilers have come to be employed in other ways.
[src:code-generation-templates/code-generation-compiler] For example, YACC (Yet Another Compiler-Compiler) takes input in Backus–Naur form and converts it to a parser in C.
[src:code-generation-templates/code-generation-compiler] Though it was initially created for automatic generation of a parser for a compiler, yacc is also often used to automate writing code that needs to be modified each time specifications are changed.
[src:code-generation-templates/code-generation-compiler] Many integrated development environments (IDEs) support some form of automatic source-code generation, often using algorithms in common with compiler code generators, although commonly less complicated.
[src:code-generation-templates/code-generation-compiler] In general, a syntax and semantic analyzer tries to retrieve the program's structure from the source code, while a code generator uses this structural information (e.g., data types) to produce code.
[src:code-generation-templates/code-generation-compiler] In other words, the former *adds* information while the latter *loses* some.
[src:code-generation-templates/code-generation-compiler] One consequence of this information loss is that reflection becomes difficult or even impossible.
[src:code-generation-templates/code-generation-compiler] To counter this problem, code generators often embed syntactic and semantic information and the code necessary for execution.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] In computer programming, a **macro** (short for "**macro instruction**"; from Greek μακρο*-* 'long, large') is a rule or pattern that specifies how a certain input should be mapped to a replacement output.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Applying a macro to an input is known as **macro expansion**.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] The input and output may be a sequence of lexical tokens or characters, or a syntax tree.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Character macros are supported in software applications to make it easy to invoke common command sequences.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Token and tree macros are supported in some programming languages to enable code reuse or to extend the language, sometimes for domain-specific languages.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Macros are used to make a sequence of computing instructions available to the programmer as a single program statement, making the programming task less tedious and less error-prone.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Thus, they are called "macros" because a "big" block of code can be expanded from a "small" sequence of characters.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Macros often allow positional or keyword parameters that dictate what the conditional assembler program generates and have been used to create entire programs or program suites according to such variables as operating system, platform or other factors.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] The term derives from "macro instruction", and such expansions were originally used in generating assembly language code.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] During the 1980s, macro programs – originally SmartKey, then SuperKey, KeyWorks, Prokey – were very popular, first as a means to automatically format screenplays, then for a variety of user-input tasks.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] These programs were based on the terminate-and-stay-resident mode of operation and applied to all keyboard input, no matter in which context it occurred.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] They have to some extent fallen into obsolescence following the advent of mouse-driven user interfaces and the availability of keyboard and mouse macros in applications, such as word processors and spreadsheets, making it possible to create application-sensitive keyboard macros.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Keyboard macros can be used in massively multiplayer online role-playing games (MMORPGs) to perform repetitive, but lucrative tasks, thus accumulating resources.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] As this is done without human effort, it can skew the economy of the game.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] For this reason, use of macros is a violation of the TOS or EULA of most MMORPGs, and their administrators spend considerable effort to suppress them.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Keyboard and mouse macros that are created using an application's built-in macro features are sometimes called **application macros**.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] They are created by carrying out the sequence once and letting the application record the actions.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] An underlying macro programming language, most commonly a scripting language, with direct access to the features of the application may also exist.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] The programmers' text editor Emacs (short for "editing macros") follows this idea to a conclusion.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] In effect, most of the editor is made of macros.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Emacs was originally devised as a set of macros in the editing language TECO; it was later ported to dialects of Lisp.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Another programmers' text editor, Vim (a descendant of vi), also has an implementation of keyboard macros.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] It can record into a register (macro) what a person types on the keyboard and it can be replayed or edited just like VBA macros for Microsoft Office.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Vim also has a scripting language called Vimscript to create macros.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Visual Basic for Applications (VBA) is a programming language included in Microsoft Office from Office 97 through Office 2019 (although it was available in some components of Office prior to Office 97).
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] However, its function has evolved from and replaced the macro languages that were originally included in some of these applications.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] XEDIT, running on the Conversational Monitor System (CMS) component of VM, supports macros written in EXEC, EXEC2 and REXX, and some CMS commands were actually wrappers around XEDIT macros.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] The Hessling Editor (THE), a partial clone of XEDIT, supports Rexx macros using Regina and Open Object REXX (oorexx).
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Many common applications, and some on PCs, use Rexx as a scripting language.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] VBA has access to most Microsoft Windows system calls and executes when documents are opened.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] This makes it relatively easy to write computer viruses in VBA, commonly known as macro viruses.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] In the mid-to-late 1990s, this became one of the most common types of computer virus.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] However, during the late 1990s and to date, Microsoft has been patching and updating its programs.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] In addition, current anti-virus programs immediately counteract such attacks.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] A **parameterized macro** is a macro that is able to insert given objects into its expansion.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] This gives the macro some of the power of a function.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] This causes `PI` to always be replaced with `3.14159` wherever it occurs.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] What this macro expands to depends on what argument *x* is passed to it.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Parameterized macros are a useful source-level mechanism for performing in-line expansion, but in languages such as C where they use simple textual substitution, they have a number of severe disadvantages over other mechanisms for performing in-line expansion, such as inline functions.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] The parameterized macros used in languages such as Lisp, PL/I and Scheme, on the other hand, are much more powerful, able to make decisions about what code to produce based on their arguments; thus, they can effectively be used to perform run-time code generation.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Languages such as C and some assembly languages have rudimentary macro systems, implemented as preprocessors to the compiler or assembler.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] C preprocessor macros work by simple textual substitution at the token, rather than the character level.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] However, the macro facilities of more sophisticated assemblers, e.g., IBM High Level Assembler (HLASM) can't be implemented with a preprocessor; the code for assembling instructions and data is interspersed with the code for assembling macro invocations.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] A classic use of macros is in the computer typesetting system TeX and its derivatives, where most functionality is based on macros.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] MacroML is an experimental system that seeks to reconcile static typing and macro systems.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Nemerle has typed syntax macros, and one productive way to think of these syntax macros is as a multi-stage computation.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Some major applications have been written as text macro invoked by other applications, e.g., by XEDIT in CMS.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Some languages, such as PHP, can be embedded in free-format text, or the source code of other languages.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] The mechanism by which the code fragments are recognised (for instance, being bracketed by `<?php` and `?>`) is similar to a textual macro language, but they are much more powerful, fully featured languages.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Macros in the PL/I language are written in a subset of PL/I itself: the compiler executes "preprocessor statements" at compilation time, and the output of this execution forms part of the code that is compiled.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] The ability to use a familiar procedural language as the macro language gives power much greater than that of text substitution macros, at the expense of a larger and slower compiler.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Macros in PL/I, as well as in many assemblers, may have side effects, e.g., setting variables that other macros can access.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Frame technology's frame macros have their own command syntax but can also contain text in any language.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Each frame is both a generic component in a hierarchy of nested subassemblies, and a procedure for integrating itself with its subassembly frames (a recursive process that resolves integration conflicts in favor of higher level subassemblies).
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] The outputs are custom documents, typically compilable source modules.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Frame technology can avoid the proliferation of similar but subtly different components, an issue that has plagued software development since the invention of macros and subroutines.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Most assembly languages have less powerful procedural macro facilities, for example allowing a block of code to be repeated N times for loop unrolling; but these have a completely different syntax from the actual assembly language.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Macro systems—such as the C preprocessor described earlier—that work at the level of lexical tokens cannot preserve the lexical structure reliably.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Syntactic macro systems work instead at the level of abstract syntax trees, and preserve the lexical structure of the original program.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] The most widely used implementations of syntactic macro systems are found in Lisp-like languages.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] These languages are especially suited for this style of macro due to their uniform, parenthesized syntax (known as S-expressions).
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] In particular, uniform syntax makes it easier to determine the invocations of macros.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Lisp macros transform the program structure itself, with the full language available to express such transformations.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] While syntactic macros are often found in Lisp-like languages, they are also available in other languages such as Prolog, Erlang, Dylan, Scala, Nemerle, Rust, Elixir, Nim, Haxe, and Julia.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] They are also available as third-party extensions to JavaScript and C#.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Before Lisp had macros, it had so-called FEXPRs, function-like operators whose inputs were not the values computed by the arguments but rather the syntactic forms of the arguments, and whose output were values to be used in the computation.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] In other words, FEXPRs were implemented at the same level as EVAL, and provided a window into the meta-evaluation layer.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] This was generally found to be a difficult model to reason about effectively.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] In 1963, Timothy Hart proposed adding macros to Lisp 1.5 in AI Memo 57: MACRO Definitions for LISP.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] An anaphoric macro is a type of programming macro that deliberately captures some form supplied to the macro which may be referred to by an anaphor (an expression referring to another).
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Anaphoric macros first appeared in Paul Graham's On Lisp and their name is a reference to linguistic anaphora—the use of words as a substitute for preceding words.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Hygienic macros have been standardized for Scheme in the R5RS, R6RS, and R7RS standards.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] A number of competing implementations of hygienic macros exist such as `syntax-rules`, `syntax-case`, explicit renaming, and syntactic closures.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Both `syntax-rules` and `syntax-case` have been standardized in the Scheme standards.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Recently, Racket has combined the notions of hygienic macros with a "tower of evaluators", so that the syntactic expansion time of one macro system is the ordinary runtime of another block of code, and showed how to apply interleaved expansion and parsing in a non-parenthesized language.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] A number of languages other than Scheme either implement hygienic macros or implement partially hygienic systems.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Examples include Scala, Rust, Elixir, Julia, Dylan, Nim, and Nemerle.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] ) enables the creation of new syntactic constructs (e.g.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] ) indistinguishable from those built into the language.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] , it is possible to define the latter in terms of the former using macros.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] and hygienic macros, which enables a programmer to design their own control abstractions, such as looping and early exit constructs, without the need to build them into the language.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] can be implemented in a way that is both natural and efficient.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Macros can also be used to introduce new binding constructs.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] into the application of a function to a set of arguments.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Felleisen conjectures that these three categories make up the primary legitimate uses of macros in such a system.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Others have proposed alternative uses of macros, such as anaphoric macros in macro systems that are unhygienic or allow selective unhygienic transformation.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] The interaction of macros and other language features has been a productive area of research.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] For example, components and modules are useful for large-scale programming, but the interaction of macros and these other constructs must be defined for their use together.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Module and component-systems that can interact with macros have been proposed for Scheme and other languages with macros.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] For example, the Racket language extends the notion of a macro system to a syntactic tower, where macros can be written in languages including macros, using hygiene to ensure that syntactic layers are distinct and allowing modules to export macros to other modules.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Macros are normally used to map a short string (macro invocation) to a longer sequence of instructions.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Another, less common, use of macros is to do the reverse: to map a sequence of instructions to a macro string.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] This was the approach taken by the STAGE2 Mobile Programming System, which used a rudimentary macro compiler (called SIMCMP) to map the specific instruction set of a given computer into *machine-independent* macros.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Applications (notably compilers) written in these machine-independent macros can then be run without change on any computer equipped with the rudimentary macro compiler.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] The first application run in such a context is a more sophisticated and powerful macro compiler, written in the machine-independent macro language.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] This macro compiler is applied to itself, in a bootstrap fashion, to produce a compiled and much more efficient version of itself.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] The advantage of this approach is that complex applications can be ported from one computer to a very different computer with very little effort (for each target machine architecture, just the writing of the rudimentary macro compiler).
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] The advent of modern programming languages, notably C, for which compilers are available on virtually all computers, has rendered such an approach superfluous.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] This was, however, one of the first instances (if not the first) of compiler bootstrapping.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] A macro instruction embedded in the otherwise assembly source code would be processed by a macro compiler, a preprocessor to the assembler, to replace the macro with one or more assembly instructions.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] The resulting code, pure assembly, would be translated to machine code by the assembler.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Two of the earliest programming installations to develop macro languages for the IBM 705 computer were at Dow Chemical Corp. in Delaware and the Air Material Command, Ballistics Missile Logistics Office in California.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Some consider macro instructions as an intermediate step between assembly language programming and the high-level programming languages that followed, such as FORTRAN and COBOL.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] By the late 1950s the macro language was followed by the Macro Assemblers.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] This was a combination of both where one program served both functions, that of a macro pre-processor and an assembler in the same package.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Early examples are FORTRAN Assembly Program (FAP) and Macro Assembly Program (IBMAP) on the IBM 709, 7094, 7040 and 7044, and Autocoder on the 7070/7072/7074.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Eastwood and Douglas McIlroy of Bell Labs introduced conditional and recursive macros into the popular SAP assembler, creating what is known as Macro SAP.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] McIlroy's 1960 paper was seminal in the area of extending any (including high-level) programming languages through macro processors.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Macro Assemblers allowed assembly language programmers to implement their own macro-language and allowed limited portability of code between two machines running the same CPU but different operating systems, for example, early versions of MS-DOS and CP/M-86.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] The macro library would need to be written for each target machine but not the overall assembly language program.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Note that more powerful macro assemblers allowed use of conditional assembly constructs in macro instructions that could generate different code on different machines or different operating systems, reducing the need for multiple libraries.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] In the 1980s and early 1990s, desktop PCs were only running at a few MHz and assembly language routines were commonly used to speed up programs written in C, Fortran, Pascal and others.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] These languages, at the time, used different calling conventions.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Macros could be used to interface routines written in assembly language to the front end of applications written in almost any language.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Again, the basic assembly language code remained the same, only the macro libraries needed to be written for each target language.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] In modern operating systems such as Unix and its derivatives, operating system access is provided through subroutines, usually provided by dynamic libraries.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] High-level languages such as C offer comprehensive access to operating system functions, obviating the need for assembler language programs for such functionality.
[src:code-generation-templates/macro-computer-science] Moreover, standard libraries of several newer programming languages, such as Go, actively discourage the use of syscalls in favor of platform-agnostic libraries as well if not necessary, to improve portability and security.
[src:code-generation-templates/metaprogramming] Metaprogramming can be used to move computations from runtime to compile time, to generate code using compile time computations, and to enable self-modifying code.
[src:code-generation-templates/metaprogramming] The ability of a programming language to be its own metalanguage allows reflective programming, and is termed *reflection*.
[src:code-generation-templates/metaprogramming] Reflection is a valuable language feature to facilitate metaprogramming.
[src:code-generation-templates/metaprogramming] Metaprogramming was popular in the 1970s and 1980s using list processing languages such as Lisp.
[src:code-generation-templates/metaprogramming] Lisp machine hardware gained some notice in the 1980s, and enabled applications that could process code.
[src:code-generation-templates/metaprogramming] They were often used for artificial intelligence applications.
[src:code-generation-templates/metaprogramming] Metaprogramming enables developers to write programs and develop code that falls under the generic programming paradigm.
[src:code-generation-templates/metaprogramming] Having the programming language itself as a first-class data type (as in Lisp, Prolog, SNOBOL, or Rebol) is also very useful; this is known as *homoiconicity*.
[src:code-generation-templates/metaprogramming] Generic programming invokes a metaprogramming facility within a language by allowing one to write code without the concern of specifying data types since they can be supplied as parameters when used.
[src:code-generation-templates/metaprogramming] Metaprogramming usually works in one of three ways.
[src:code-generation-templates/metaprogramming] The second approach is dynamic execution of expressions that contain programming commands, often composed from strings, but can also be from other methods using arguments or context, like JavaScript.
[src:code-generation-templates/metaprogramming] Thus, "programs can write programs." Although both approaches can be used in the same language, most languages tend to lean toward one or the other.
[src:code-generation-templates/metaprogramming] The third approach is to step outside the language entirely.
[src:code-generation-templates/metaprogramming] General purpose program transformation systems such as compilers, which accept language descriptions and carry out arbitrary transformations on those languages, are direct implementations of general metaprogramming.
[src:code-generation-templates/metaprogramming] This allows metaprogramming to be applied to virtually any target language without regard to whether that target language has any metaprogramming abilities of its own.
[src:code-generation-templates/metaprogramming] One can see this at work with Scheme and how it allows tackling some limits faced in C by using constructs that are part of the Scheme language to extend C.
[src:code-generation-templates/metaprogramming] Lisp is probably the quintessential language with metaprogramming facilities, both because of its historical precedence and because of the simplicity and power of its metaprogramming.
[src:code-generation-templates/metaprogramming] In Lisp metaprogramming, the unquote operator (typically a comma) introduces code that is evaluated at program definition time rather than at run time.
[src:code-generation-templates/metaprogramming] The metaprogramming language is thus identical to the host programming language, and existing Lisp routines can be directly reused for metaprogramming if desired.
[src:code-generation-templates/metaprogramming] This approach has been implemented in other languages by incorporating an interpreter in the program, which works directly with the program's data.
[src:code-generation-templates/metaprogramming] There are implementations of this kind for some common high-level languages, such as RemObjects’ Pascal Script for Object Pascal.
[src:code-generation-templates/metaprogramming] This script (or program) generates a new 993-line program that prints out the numbers 1–992.
[src:code-generation-templates/metaprogramming] This is only an illustration of how to use code to write more code; it is not the most efficient way to print out a list of numbers.
[src:code-generation-templates/metaprogramming] Nonetheless, a programmer can write and execute this metaprogram in less than a minute, and will have generated over 1000 lines of code in that amount of time.
[src:code-generation-templates/metaprogramming] A quine is a special kind of metaprogram that produces its own source code as its output.
[src:code-generation-templates/metaprogramming] Quines are generally of recreational or theoretical interest only.
[src:code-generation-templates/metaprogramming] Not all metaprogramming involves generative programming.
[src:code-generation-templates/metaprogramming] One style of generative approach is to employ domain-specific languages (DSLs).
[src:code-generation-templates/metaprogramming] One usage of metaprogramming is to instrument programs in order to do dynamic program analysis.
[src:code-generation-templates/metaprogramming] Some argue that there is a sharp learning curve to make complete use of metaprogramming features.
[src:code-generation-templates/metaprogramming] Since metaprogramming gives more flexibility and configurability at runtime, misuse or incorrect use of metaprogramming can result in unwarranted and unexpected errors that can be extremely difficult to debug to an average developer.
[src:code-generation-templates/metaprogramming] It can introduce risks in the system and make it more vulnerable if not used with care.
[src:code-generation-templates/metaprogramming] Some of the common problems, which can occur due to wrong use of metaprogramming are inability of the compiler to identify missing configuration parameters, invalid or incorrect data can result in unknown exception or different results.
[src:code-generation-templates/metaprogramming] Due to this, some believe that only high-skilled developers should work on developing features which exercise metaprogramming in a language or platform and average developers must learn how to use these features as part of convention.
[src:code-generation-templates/metaprogramming] The IBM/360 and derivatives had powerful macro assembler facilities that were often used to generate complete assembly language programs or sections of programs (for different operating systems for instance).
[src:code-generation-templates/metaprogramming] Macros provided with CICS transaction processing system had assembler macros that generated COBOL statements as a pre-processing step.
[src:code-generation-templates/metaprogramming] Other assemblers, such as MASM, also support macros.
[src:code-generation-templates/metaprogramming] Use of dependent types allows proving that generated code is never invalid.
[src:code-generation-templates/metaprogramming] However, this approach is leading-edge and rarely found outside of research programming languages.
[src:code-generation-templates/metaprogramming] The list of notable metaprogramming systems is maintained at List of program transformation systems.
[src:code-generation-templates/preprocessor] In computer science, a **preprocessor** (or **precompiler**) is a program that processes its input data to produce output that is used as input in another program.
[src:code-generation-templates/preprocessor] The output is said to be a **preprocessed** form of the input data, which is often used by some subsequent programs like compilers.
[src:code-generation-templates/preprocessor] The amount and kind of processing done depends on the nature of the preprocessor; some preprocessors are only capable of performing relatively simple textual substitutions and macro expansions, while others have the power of full-fledged programming languages.
[src:code-generation-templates/preprocessor] A common example from computer programming is the processing performed on source code before the next step of compilation.
[src:code-generation-templates/preprocessor] In some computer languages (e.g., C and PL/I) there is a phase of translation known as *preprocessing*.
[src:code-generation-templates/preprocessor] It can also include macro processing, file inclusion and language extensions.
[src:code-generation-templates/preprocessor] They typically perform macro substitution, textual inclusion of other files, and conditional compilation or inclusion.
[src:code-generation-templates/preprocessor] The most common example of this is the C preprocessor, which takes lines beginning with '#' as directives.
[src:code-generation-templates/preprocessor] The C preprocessor does not expect its input to use the syntax of the C language.
[src:code-generation-templates/preprocessor] Some languages take a different approach and use built-in language features to achieve similar things.
[src:code-generation-templates/preprocessor] Other lexical preprocessors include the general-purpose m4, most commonly used in cross-platform build systems such as autoconf, and GEMA, an open source macro processor which operates on patterns of context.
[src:code-generation-templates/preprocessor] Syntactic preprocessors were introduced with the Lisp family of languages.
[src:code-generation-templates/preprocessor] Their role is to transform syntax trees according to a number of user-defined rules.
[src:code-generation-templates/preprocessor] For some programming languages, the rules are written in the same language as the program (compile-time reflection).
[src:code-generation-templates/preprocessor] Some other languages rely on a fully external language to define the transformations, such as the XSLT preprocessor for XML, or its statically typed counterpart CDuce.
[src:code-generation-templates/preprocessor] Syntactic preprocessors are typically used to customize the syntax of a language, extend a language by adding new primitives, or embed a domain-specific programming language (DSL) inside a general purpose language.
[src:code-generation-templates/preprocessor] A good example of syntax customization is the existence of two different syntaxes in the Objective Caml programming language.
[src:code-generation-templates/preprocessor] Programs may be written indifferently using the "normal syntax" or the "revised syntax", and may be pretty-printed with either syntax on demand.
[src:code-generation-templates/preprocessor] Similarly, a number of programs written in OCaml customize the syntax of the language by the addition of new operators.
[src:code-generation-templates/preprocessor] The best examples of language extension through macros are found in the Lisp family of languages.
[src:code-generation-templates/preprocessor] While the languages, by themselves, are simple dynamically typed functional cores, the standard distributions of Scheme or Common Lisp permit imperative or object-oriented programming, as well as static typing.
[src:code-generation-templates/preprocessor] Almost all of these features are implemented by syntactic preprocessing, although it bears noting that the "macro expansion" phase of compilation is handled by the compiler in Lisp.
[src:code-generation-templates/preprocessor] This can still be considered a form of preprocessing, since it takes place before other phases of compilation.
[src:code-generation-templates/preprocessor] One of the unusual features of the Lisp family of languages is the possibility of using macros to create an internal DSL.
[src:code-generation-templates/preprocessor] Typically, in a large Lisp-based project, a module may be written in a variety of such minilanguages, one perhaps using a SQL-based dialect of Lisp, another written in a dialect specialized for GUIs or pretty-printing, etc.
[src:code-generation-templates/preprocessor] Common Lisp's standard library contains an example of this level of syntactic abstraction in the form of the LOOP macro, which implements an Algol-like minilanguage to describe complex iteration, while still enabling the use of standard Lisp operators.
[src:code-generation-templates/preprocessor] The MetaOCaml preprocessor/language provides similar features for external DSLs.
[src:code-generation-templates/preprocessor] This preprocessor takes the description of the semantics of a language (i.e. an interpreter) and, by combining compile-time interpretation and code generation, turns that definition into a compiler to the OCaml programming language—and from that language, either to bytecode or to native code.
[src:code-generation-templates/preprocessor] Most preprocessors are specific to a particular data processing task (e.g., compiling the C language).
[src:code-generation-templates/preprocessor] A preprocessor may be promoted as being *general purpose*, meaning that it is not aimed at a specific usage or programming language, and is intended to be used for a wide variety of text processing tasks.
[src:code-generation-templates/preprocessor] M4 is probably the most well known example of such a general purpose preprocessor, although the C preprocessor is sometimes used in a non-C specific role.
[src:code-generation-templates/template-metaprogramming] Template metaprogramming was, in a sense, discovered accidentally.
[src:code-generation-templates/template-metaprogramming] Some other languages support similar, if not more powerful, compile-time facilities (such as Lisp's macros).
[src:code-generation-templates/template-metaprogramming] The use of templates as a metaprogramming technique requires two distinct operations: a template must be defined, and a defined template must be instantiated.
[src:code-generation-templates/template-metaprogramming] The generic form of the generated source code is described in the template definition, and when the template is instantiated, the generic form in the template is used to generate a specific set of source code.
[src:code-generation-templates/template-metaprogramming] Template metaprogramming is Turing-complete, meaning that any computation expressible by a computer program can be computed, in some form, by a template metaprogram.
[src:code-generation-templates/template-metaprogramming] A macro is a piece of code that executes at compile time and either performs textual manipulation of code to-be compiled (e.g.
[src:code-generation-templates/template-metaprogramming] C++ macros) or manipulates the abstract syntax tree being produced by the compiler (e.g.
[src:code-generation-templates/template-metaprogramming] Textual macros are notably more independent of the syntax of the language being manipulated, as they merely change the in-memory text of the source code right before compilation.
[src:code-generation-templates/template-metaprogramming] Template metaprograms have no mutable variables— that is, no variable can change value once it has been initialized, therefore template metaprogramming can be seen as a form of functional programming.
[src:code-generation-templates/template-metaprogramming] In fact many template implementations implement flow control only through recursion, as seen in the example below.
[src:code-generation-templates/template-metaprogramming] Though the syntax of template metaprogramming is usually very different from the programming language it is used with, it has practical uses.
[src:code-generation-templates/template-metaprogramming] The code above will execute at run time to determine the factorial value of the literals `0` and `4`.
[src:code-generation-templates/template-metaprogramming] The code above calculates the factorial value of the literals `0` and `4` at compile time and uses the results as if they were precalculated constants.
[src:code-generation-templates/template-metaprogramming] To be able to use templates in this manner, the compiler must know the value of its parameters at compile time, which has the natural precondition that `Factorial<X>::value` can only be used if `X` is known at compile time.
[src:code-generation-templates/template-metaprogramming] In other words, `X` must be a constant literal or a constant expression.
[src:code-generation-templates/template-metaprogramming] In C++11 and C++20, constexpr and consteval were introduced to let the compiler execute code.
[src:code-generation-templates/template-metaprogramming] Using `constexpr` and `consteval`, one can use the usual recursive factorial definition with the non-templated syntax.
[src:code-generation-templates/template-metaprogramming] The factorial example above is one example of compile-time code optimization in that all factorials used by the program are pre-compiled and injected as numeric constants at compilation, saving both run-time overhead and memory footprint.
[src:code-generation-templates/template-metaprogramming] It is, however, a relatively minor optimization.
[src:code-generation-templates/template-metaprogramming] As another, more significant, example of compile-time loop unrolling, template metaprogramming can be used to create length-*n* vector classes (where *n* is known at compile time).
[src:code-generation-templates/template-metaprogramming] The benefit over a more traditional length-*n* vector is that the loops can be unrolled, resulting in very optimized code.
[src:code-generation-templates/template-metaprogramming] As an example, consider the addition operator.
[src:code-generation-templates/template-metaprogramming] The compiler's optimizer should be able to unroll the `for` loop because the template parameter `Length` is a constant at compile time.
[src:code-generation-templates/template-metaprogramming] However, care must be taken as this may cause code bloat, since separate unrolled code will be generated for each 'N'(vector size) the template is instantiated with.
[src:code-generation-templates/template-metaprogramming] where all invocations of `virtual` methods will be those of the most-derived class.
[src:code-generation-templates/template-metaprogramming] This *dynamically polymorphic* behaviour is (typically) obtained by the creation of virtual look-up tables for classes with virtual methods, tables that are traversed at run time to identify the method to be invoked.
[src:code-generation-templates/template-metaprogramming] Thus, *run-time polymorphism* necessarily entails execution overhead (though on modern architectures the overhead is small).
[src:code-generation-templates/template-metaprogramming] However, in many cases the polymorphic behaviour needed is invariant and can be determined at compile time.
[src:code-generation-templates/template-metaprogramming] Then the Curiously Recurring Template Pattern (CRTP) can be used to achieve **static polymorphism**, which is an imitation of polymorphism in programming code but which is resolved at compile time and thus does away with run-time virtual-table lookups.
[src:code-generation-templates/template-metaprogramming] As an example of real-world usage, the CRTP is used in the Boost iterator library.
[src:code-generation-templates/template-metaprogramming] Another similar use is the "Barton–Nackman trick", sometimes referred to as "restricted template expansion", where common functionality can be placed in a base class that is used not as a contract but as a necessary component to enforce conformant behaviour while minimising code redundancy.
[src:code-generation-templates/template-metaprogramming] The benefit of static tables is the replacement of "expensive" calculations with a simple array indexing operation (for examples, see lookup table).
[src:code-generation-templates/template-metaprogramming] In C++, there exists more than one way to generate a static table at compile time.
[src:code-generation-templates/template-metaprogramming] The following listing shows an example of creating a very simple table by using recursive structs and variadic templates.
[src:code-generation-templates/template-metaprogramming] The idea behind this is that the struct Helper recursively inherits from a struct with one more template argument (in this example calculated as Index * Index) until the specialization of the template ends the recursion at a size of 10 elements.
[src:code-generation-templates/template-metaprogramming] The specialization simply uses the variable argument list as elements for the array.
[src:code-generation-templates/template-metaprogramming] The compiler will produce code similar to the following (taken from clang called with -Xclang -ast-print -fsyntax-only).
